					<div id=3D"contentSub"><div id=3D"mw-content-subtitle"></div></div>
				=09
				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">In =
statistics, a measure of variation</div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">For other us=
es, see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_deviation_(disamb=
iguation)" class=3D"mw-disambig" title=3D"Standard deviation (disambiguatio=
n)">Standard deviation (disambiguation)</a>.</div>
<p class=3D"mw-empty-elt">
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Standard_deviation_diagram.svg" class=3D"mw-f=
ile-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons=
/thumb/8/8c/Standard_deviation_diagram.svg/250px-Standard_deviation_diagram=
.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"125" class=3D"mw-file-=
element" data-file-width=3D"400" data-file-height=3D"200"></a><figcaption>A=
 plot of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normal_distribution" titl=
e=3D"Normal distribution">normal distribution</a> (or bell-shaped curve) wh=
ere each band has a width of 1 standard deviation&nbsp;=E2=80=93 See also: =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/68%E2%80%9395%E2%80%9399.7_rule" t=
itle=3D"68=E2=80=9395=E2=80=9399.7 rule">68=E2=80=9395=E2=80=9399.7 rule</a=
>.</figcaption></figure>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Normal-distribution-cumulative-density-functi=
on.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.=
org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/15/Normal-distribution-cumulative-density-fun=
ction.svg/250px-Normal-distribution-cumulative-density-function.svg.png" de=
coding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"182" class=3D"mw-file-element" dat=
a-file-width=3D"899" data-file-height=3D"655"></a><figcaption>Cumulative pr=
obability of a normal distribution with expected value 0 and standard devia=
tion 1</figcaption></figure>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics" title=3D"Statist=
ics">statistics</a>, the <b>standard deviation</b> is a measure of the amou=
nt of variation of the values of a variable about its <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Expected_value" title=3D"Expected value">mean</a>.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-StatNotes_1-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Standard_deviation#cite_note-StatNotes-1"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A low =
standard <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deviation_(statistics)" t=
itle=3D"Deviation (statistics)">deviation</a> indicates that the values ten=
d to be close to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mean" title=
=3D"Mean">mean</a> (also called the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Expected_value" title=3D"Expected value">expected value</a>) of the set, =
while a high standard deviation indicates that the values are spread out ov=
er a wider range.  Standard deviation may be abbreviated <b>SD</b> or <b>st=
d dev</b>, and is most commonly represented in mathematical texts and equat=
ions by the lowercase <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greek_alphab=
et" title=3D"Greek alphabet">Greek letter</a> <b><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Sigma" title=3D"Sigma">=CF=83</a></b> (sigma), for the <b>po=
pulation standard deviation</b>, or the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Latin_script" title=3D"Latin script">Latin letter</a> <i><b><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S" title=3D"S">s</a></b></i>, for the <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sample_standard_deviation" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Sample standard deviation">sample standard deviation</=
a>.
</p><p>The standard deviation of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Random_variable" title=3D"Random variable">random variable</a>, <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sample_(statistics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" t=
itle=3D"Sample (statistics)">sample</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Statistical_population" title=3D"Statistical population">statistical=
 population</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_set" title=
=3D"Data set">data set</a>, or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pro=
bability_distribution" title=3D"Probability distribution">probability distr=
ibution</a> is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square_root" ti=
tle=3D"Square root">square root</a> of its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Variance" title=3D"Variance">variance</a>. (For a finite populatio=
n, variance is the average of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Squared_deviations_from_the_mean" title=3D"Squared deviations from the mean=
">squared deviations from the mean</a>.) A useful property of the standard =
deviation is that, unlike the variance, it is expressed in the same unit as=
 the data. Standard deviation can also be used to calculate <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_error" title=3D"Standard error">standard=
 error</a> for a finite sample, and to determine <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Statistical_significance" title=3D"Statistical significance"=
>statistical significance</a>.
</p><p>When only a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_sam=
ple" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Statistical sample">sample</a> of data =
from a population is available, the term <i>standard deviation of the sampl=
e</i> or <i>sample standard deviation</i> can refer to either the above-men=
tioned quantity as applied to those data, or to a modified quantity that is=
 an unbiased estimate of the <i>population standard deviation</i> (the stan=
dard deviation of the entire population).
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Relationship_with_standard_=
error_and_statistical_significance">Relationship with standard error and st=
atistical significance</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw=
-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.p=
hp?title=3DStandard_deviation&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"E=
dit section: Relationship with standard error and statistical significance"=
><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span=
></div>
<p>The standard deviation of a population or sample and the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_error" title=3D"Standard error">standard=
 error</a> of a statistic (e.g., of the sample mean) are quite different, b=
ut related. The sample mean's standard error is the standard deviation of t=
he set of means that would be found by drawing an <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Infinity" title=3D"Infinity">infinite</a> number of repeate=
d samples from the population and computing a mean for each sample.  The me=
an's standard error turns out to equal the population standard deviation di=
vided by the square root of the sample size, and is estimated by using the =
sample standard deviation divided by the square root of the sample size. Fo=
r example, a poll's standard error (what is reported as the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Margin_of_error" title=3D"Margin of error">margin=
 of error</a> of the poll) is the expected standard deviation of the estima=
ted mean if the same poll were to be conducted multiple times. Thus, the st=
andard error estimates the standard deviation of an estimate, which itself =
measures how much the estimate depends on the particular sample that was ta=
ken from the population.=20
</p><p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Science" title=3D"Scienc=
e">science</a>, it is common to report both the standard deviation of the d=
ata (as a summary statistic) and the standard error of the estimate (as a m=
easure of potential error in the findings). By convention, only effects mor=
e than two standard errors away from a null expectation are considered "<a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_significance" title=3D"St=
atistical significance">statistically significant</a>", a safeguard against=
 spurious conclusion that is really due to random sampling error.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Basic_examples">Basic examp=
les</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DStandard=
_deviation&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Basic =
examples"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</sp=
an></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Population_standard_deviati=
on_of_grades_of_eight_students">Population standard deviation of grades of =
eight students</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsec=
tion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DStandard_deviation&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit sect=
ion: Population standard deviation of grades of eight students"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Suppose that the entire <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statist=
ical_population" title=3D"Statistical population">population</a> of interes=
t is eight students in a particular class.
Their marks are the following eight values:
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle 2,\ 4,\ 4,\ 4,\ 5,\ 5,\ 7,\ 9.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mn>2</mn>
        <mo>,</mo>
        <mtext>&nbsp;</mtext>
        <mn>4</mn>
        <mo>,</mo>
        <mtext>&nbsp;</mtext>
        <mn>4</mn>
        <mo>,</mo>
        <mtext>&nbsp;</mtext>
        <mn>4</mn>
        <mo>,</mo>
        <mtext>&nbsp;</mtext>
        <mn>5</mn>
        <mo>,</mo>
        <mtext>&nbsp;</mtext>
        <mn>5</mn>
        <mo>,</mo>
        <mtext>&nbsp;</mtext>
        <mn>7</mn>
        <mo>,</mo>
        <mtext>&nbsp;</mtext>
        <mn>9.</mn>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle 2,\ 4,\ 4,\ 4=
,\ 5,\ 5,\ 7,\ 9.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/e7c0d44f87d7dcc46301efa28031639498d4313e" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -0.671ex; width:21.249ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle 2=
,\ 4,\ 4,\ 4,\ 5,\ 5,\ 7,\ 9.}"></span>
</p><p>For a finite set of numbers, the population standard deviation is fo=
und by taking the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square_root" tit=
le=3D"Square root">square root</a> of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Average" title=3D"Average">average</a> of the squared deviations of=
 the values subtracted from their average value, that is:
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle \sigma =3D{\sqrt {\mathrm {average} \left((v-\mu )^{2}{\text{ f=
or }}v\in \mathrm {values} \right)}}{\text{ where }}\mu =3D\mathrm {average=
} (\mathrm {values} ).}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>=CF=83<!-- =CF=83 --></mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <msqrt>
            <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
              <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">a</mi>
              <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">v</mi>
              <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">e</mi>
              <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">r</mi>
              <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">a</mi>
              <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">g</mi>
              <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">e</mi>
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              <mo>(</mo>
              <mrow>
                <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
                <mi>v</mi>
                <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
                <mi>=CE=BC<!-- =CE=BC --></mi>
                <msup>
                  <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
                  <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                    <mn>2</mn>
                  </mrow>
                </msup>
                <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                  <mtext>&nbsp;for&nbsp;</mtext>
                </mrow>
                <mi>v</mi>
                <mo>=E2=88=88<!-- =E2=88=88 --></mo>
                <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                  <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">v</mi>
                  <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">a</mi>
                  <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">l</mi>
                  <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">u</mi>
                  <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">e</mi>
                  <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">s</mi>
                </mrow>
              </mrow>
              <mo>)</mo>
            </mrow>
          </msqrt>
        </mrow>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mtext>&nbsp;where&nbsp;</mtext>
        </mrow>
        <mi>=CE=BC<!-- =CE=BC --></mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">a</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">v</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">e</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">r</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">a</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">g</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">e</mi>
        </mrow>
