> of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">X</span>.
</p><p>The standard deviation of a probability distribution is the same as =
that of a random variable having that distribution.=20
</p><p>Not all random variables have a standard deviation. If the distribut=
ion has <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fat_tails" class=3D"mw-red=
irect" title=3D"Fat tails">fat tails</a> going out to infinity, the standar=
d deviation might not exist, because the integral might not converge. The <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normal_distribution" title=3D"Norma=
l distribution">normal distribution</a> has tails going out to infinity, bu=
t its mean and standard deviation do exist, because the tails diminish quic=
kly enough. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pareto_distributio=
n" title=3D"Pareto distribution">Pareto distribution</a> with parameter <sp=
an class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-ma=
