m {d} }x}}\,,~~{\text{ where }}~~\mu \equiv \int _{\mathbf {X} }x\,p(x)\,{\=
mathrm {d} }x\,,}"></span>
</p><p>and where the integrals are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Definite_integral" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Definite integral">defin=
ite integrals</a> taken for <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-styl=
e:italic;">x</span> ranging over <b><span class=3D"texhtml">X</span></b>, w=
hich represents the set of possible values of the random variable&nbsp;<spa=
n class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">X</span>.
</p><p>In the case of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parametric=
_model" title=3D"Parametric model">parametric family of distributions</a>, =
the standard deviation can often be expressed in terms of the parameters fo=
r the underlying distribution. For example, in the case of the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Log-normal_distribution" title=3D"Log-normal d=
istribution">log-normal distribution</a> with parameters <span class=3D"tex=
html mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=BC</span> and <span class=3D"te=
xhtml"><var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">=CF=83</var><sup>2</sup></span> f=
or the underlying normal distribution, the standard deviation of the log-no=
rmal variable is given by the expression
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle {\sqrt {\left(e^{\sigma ^{2}}-1\right)\ e^{2\mu +\sigma ^{2}}}}=
\,.}">
