<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Estimation">Estimation<span=
 class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Estimation"></span><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Sam=
ple_standard_deviation"></span></h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
w/index.php?title=3DStandard_deviation&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" t=
itle=3D"Edit section: Estimation"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sample_variance" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sample variance">Sample variance</a></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unbiased_estimation_=
of_standard_deviation" title=3D"Unbiased estimation of standard deviation">=
Unbiased estimation of standard deviation</a></div>
<p>One can find the standard deviation of an entire population in cases (su=
ch as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standardized_testing_(statis=
tics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Standardized testing (statistics)">st=
andardized testing</a>) where every member of a population is sampled. In c=
ases where that cannot be done, the standard deviation <i>=CF=83</i> is est=
imated by examining a random sample taken from the population and computing=
 a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistic" title=3D"Statistic">=
statistic</a> of the sample, which is used as an estimate of the population=
 standard deviation. Such a statistic is called an <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Estimator" title=3D"Estimator">estimator</a>, and the esti=
mator (or the value of the estimator, namely the estimate) is called a <b>s=
ample standard deviation</b>, and is denoted by <i>s</i> (possibly with mod=
ifiers).
</p><p>Unlike in the case of estimating the population mean of a normal dis=
tribution, for which the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sample_me=
an" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sample mean">sample mean</a> is a simple=
 estimator with many desirable properties (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Unbiased_estimator" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Unbiased estima=
tor">unbiased</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Efficient_estim=
ator" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Efficient estimator">efficient</a>, ma=
ximum likelihood), there is no single estimator for the standard deviation =
with all these properties, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unb=
iased_estimation_of_standard_deviation" title=3D"Unbiased estimation of sta=
ndard deviation">unbiased estimation of standard deviation</a> is a very te=
chnically involved problem. Most often, the standard deviation is estimated=
 using the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_deviation#C=
orrected_sample_standard_deviation">corrected sample standard deviation</a>=
</i> (using <i>N</i>&nbsp;=E2=88=92&nbsp;1), defined below, and this is oft=
en referred to as the "sample standard deviation", without qualifiers. Howe=
ver, other estimators are better in other respects: the uncorrected estimat=
or (using <i>N</i>) yields lower mean squared error, while using <i>N</i>&n=
bsp;=E2=88=92&nbsp;1.5 (for the normal distribution) almost completely elim=
inates bias.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Uncorrected_sample_standard=
_deviation">Uncorrected sample standard deviation</h3><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DStandard_deviation&amp;action=3Dedit&=
amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: Uncorrected sample standard deviati=
on"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></s=
pan></div>
<p>The formula for the <i>population</i> standard deviation (of a finite po=
pulation) can be applied to the sample, using the size of the sample as the=
 size of the population (though the actual population size from which the s=
ample is drawn may be much larger). This estimator, denoted by <i>s</i><sub=
><i>N</i></sub>, is known as the <i>uncorrected sample standard deviation</=
i>, or sometimes the <i>standard deviation of the sample</i> (considered as=
 the entire population), and is defined as follows:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:1_5=
-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_d=
eviation#cite_note-:1-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
