2}}}.}"></span>
</p><p>As explained above, while <i>s</i><sup>2</sup> is an unbiased estima=
tor for the population variance, <i>s</i> is still a biased estimator for t=
he population standard deviation, though markedly less biased than the unco=
rrected sample standard deviation. This estimator is commonly used and gene=
rally known simply as the "sample standard deviation". The bias may still b=
e large for small samples (<i>N</i> less than 10). As sample size increases=
, the amount of bias decreases. We obtain more information and the differen=
ce between <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span c=
lass=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none=
;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displays=
tyle {\frac {1}{N}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
