-align: -2.005ex; width:6.903ex; height:5.343ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle {\f=
rac {1}{N-1}}}"></span> becomes smaller.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Unbiased_sample_standard_de=
viation">Unbiased sample standard deviation</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsecti=
on"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DStandard_deviation&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;se=
ction=3D11" title=3D"Edit section: Unbiased sample standard deviation"><spa=
n>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></di=
v>
<p>For <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unbiased_estimation_of_stan=
dard_deviation" title=3D"Unbiased estimation of standard deviation">unbiase=
d estimation of standard deviation</a>, there is no formula that works acro=
ss all distributions, unlike for mean and variance. Instead, <span class=3D=
"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">s</span> is used as a basis, an=
d is scaled by a correction factor to produce an unbiased estimate. For the=
 normal distribution, an unbiased estimator is given by <span class=3D"texh=
tml"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num=
"><var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">s</var></span><span class=3D"sr-only">=
/</span><span class=3D"den"><var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">c</var><sub>=
4</sub></span></span>=E2=81=A0</span></span>, where the correction factor (=
which depends on <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=
N</span>) is given in terms of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Gamma_function" title=3D"Gamma function">Gamma function</a>, and equals:
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle c_{4}(N)\,=3D\,{\sqrt {\frac {2}{N-1}}}\,\,\,{\frac {\Gamma {\l=
eft({\frac {N}{2}}\right)}}{\Gamma {\left({\frac {N-1}{2}}\right)}}}.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
          <mi>c</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>4</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>N</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mspace width=3D"thinmathspace"></mspace>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mspace width=3D"thinmathspace"></mspace>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <msqrt>
            <mfrac>
              <mn>2</mn>
              <mrow>
                <mi>N</mi>
                <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
                <mn>1</mn>
              </mrow>
            </mfrac>
          </msqrt>
        </mrow>
        <mspace width=3D"thinmathspace"></mspace>
        <mspace width=3D"thinmathspace"></mspace>
        <mspace width=3D"thinmathspace"></mspace>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mrow>
              <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=CE=93<!-- =CE=93 --></mi>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mrow>
                  <mo>(</mo>
                  <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                    <mfrac>
                      <mi>N</mi>
                      <mn>2</mn>
                    </mfrac>
                  </mrow>
                  <mo>)</mo>
                </mrow>
              </mrow>
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=CE=93<!-- =CE=93 --></mi>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mrow>
                  <mo>(</mo>
                  <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                    <mfrac>
                      <mrow>
                        <mi>N</mi>
                        <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
                        <mn>1</mn>
                      </mrow>
                      <mn>2</mn>
                    </mfrac>
                  </mrow>
                  <mo>)</mo>
                </mrow>
              </mrow>
            </mrow>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle c_{4}(N)\,=3D=
\,{\sqrt {\frac {2}{N-1}}}\,\,\,{\frac {\Gamma {\left({\frac {N}{2}}\right)=
}}{\Gamma {\left({\frac {N-1}{2}}\right)}}}.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/054d6247bc73ad4f96b0e4cb515f5dcfbb559124" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -4.505ex; width:30.301ex; height:10.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle =
c_{4}(N)\,=3D\,{\sqrt {\frac {2}{N-1}}}\,\,\,{\frac {\Gamma {\left({\frac {=
N}{2}}\right)}}{\Gamma {\left({\frac {N-1}{2}}\right)}}}.}"></span>
</p><p>This arises because the sampling distribution of the sample standard=
 deviation follows a (scaled) <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chi_=
distribution" title=3D"Chi distribution">chi distribution</a>, and the corr=
ection factor is the mean of the chi distribution.
</p><p>An approximation can be given by replacing <span class=3D"texhtml"><=
var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">N</var>&nbsp;=E2=88=92&nbsp;1</span> with=
 <span class=3D"texhtml"><var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">N</var>&nbsp;=
=E2=88=92&nbsp;1.5</span>, yielding:
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle {\hat {\sigma }}=3D{\sqrt {{\frac {1}{N-1.5}}\sum _{i=3D1}^{N}\=
left(x_{i}-{\bar {x}}\right)^{2}}},}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mover>
              <mi>=CF=83<!-- =CF=83 --></mi>
              <mo stretchy=3D"false">^<!-- ^ --></mo>
            </mover>
          </mrow>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <msqrt>
            <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
              <mfrac>
                <mn>1</mn>
                <mrow>
                  <mi>N</mi>
                  <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
                  <mn>1.5</mn>
                </mrow>
              </mfrac>
            </mrow>
            <munderover>
              <mo>=E2=88=91<!-- =E2=88=91 --></mo>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mi>i</mi>
                <mo>=3D</mo>
                <mn>1</mn>
              </mrow>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mi>N</mi>
              </mrow>
            </munderover>
            <msup>
              <mrow>
                <mo>(</mo>
                <mrow>
                  <msub>
                    <mi>x</mi>
                    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                      <mi>i</mi>
                    </mrow>
                  </msub>
                  <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
                  <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                      <mover>
                        <mi>x</mi>
                        <mo stretchy=3D"false">=C2=AF<!-- =C2=AF --></mo>
                      </mover>
                    </mrow>
                  </mrow>
                </mrow>
                <mo>)</mo>
              </mrow>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mn>2</mn>
              </mrow>
            </msup>
          </msqrt>
        </mrow>
        <mo>,</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle {\hat {\sigma=
 }}=3D{\sqrt {{\frac {1}{N-1.5}}\sum _{i=3D1}^{N}\left(x_{i}-{\bar {x}}\rig=
ht)^{2}}},}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/150b3d1c5845104acd04d61ba8f91e5dcdc3240d" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -3.005ex; width:29.533ex; height:8.009ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle {=
\hat {\sigma }}=3D{\sqrt {{\frac {1}{N-1.5}}\sum _{i=3D1}^{N}\left(x_{i}-{\=
bar {x}}\right)^{2}}},}"></span>
</p><p>The error in this approximation decays quadratically (as <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:Tem=
plateStyles:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion=
"><span class=3D"num">1</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=
=3D"den"><var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">N</var><sup>2</sup></span></spa=
n>=E2=81=A0</span></span>), and it is suited for all but the smallest sampl=
es or highest precision: for <span class=3D"texhtml"><var style=3D"padding-=
right: 1px;">N</var> =3D 3</span> the bias is equal to 1.3%, and for <span =
class=3D"texhtml"><var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">N</var> =3D 9</span> t=
he bias is already less than 0.1%.
</p><p>A more accurate approximation is to replace <span class=3D"texhtml">=
<var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">N</var> =E2=88=92 1.5</span> above with =
<span class=3D"texhtml"><var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">N</var> =E2=88=
=92 1.5 + <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:Templa=
teStyles:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><=
span class=3D"num">1</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"d=
en">8(<var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">N</var> =E2=88=92 1)</span></span>=
=E2=81=A0</span></span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_deviation#cite_note-7"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p><p>For other distributions, the correct formula depends on the distribu=
tion, but a rule of thumb is to use the further refinement of the approxima=
tion:
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle {\hat {\sigma }}=3D{\sqrt {{\frac {1}{N-1.5-{\frac {1}{4}}\gamm=
a _{2}}}\sum _{i=3D1}^{N}\left(x_{i}-{\bar {x}}\right)^{2}}},}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mover>
              <mi>=CF=83<!-- =CF=83 --></mi>
              <mo stretchy=3D"false">^<!-- ^ --></mo>
            </mover>
          </mrow>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <msqrt>
            <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
              <mfrac>
                <mn>1</mn>
                <mrow>
                  <mi>N</mi>
                  <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
                  <mn>1.5</mn>
                  <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
                  <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                    <mfrac>
                      <mn>1</mn>
                      <mn>4</mn>
                    </mfrac>
                  </mrow>
                  <msub>
                    <mi>=CE=B3<!-- =CE=B3 --></mi>
                    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                      <mn>2</mn>
                    </mrow>
                  </msub>
                </mrow>
              </mfrac>
            </mrow>
            <munderover>
              <mo>=E2=88=91<!-- =E2=88=91 --></mo>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mi>i</mi>
                <mo>=3D</mo>
                <mn>1</mn>
              </mrow>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mi>N</mi>
              </mrow>
            </munderover>
            <msup>
              <mrow>
                <mo>(</mo>
                <mrow>
                  <msub>
                    <mi>x</mi>
                    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                      <mi>i</mi>
                    </mrow>
                  </msub>
                  <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
                  <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                      <mover>
                        <mi>x</mi>
                        <mo stretchy=3D"false">=C2=AF<!-- =C2=AF --></mo>
                      </mover>
                    </mrow>
                  </mrow>
                </mrow>
                <mo>)</mo>
              </mrow>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mn>2</mn>
              </mrow>
            </msup>
          </msqrt>
        </mrow>
        <mo>,</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle {\hat {\sigma=
 }}=3D{\sqrt {{\frac {1}{N-1.5-{\frac {1}{4}}\gamma _{2}}}\sum _{i=3D1}^{N}=
\left(x_{i}-{\bar {x}}\right)^{2}}},}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/3d7efb316b656c7f0cec6f45361afdbea2e41cc2" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -3.338ex; width:36.29ex; height:8.343ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle {\=
hat {\sigma }}=3D{\sqrt {{\frac {1}{N-1.5-{\frac {1}{4}}\gamma _{2}}}\sum _=
{i=3D1}^{N}\left(x_{i}-{\bar {x}}\right)^{2}}},}"></span>
</p><p>where <span class=3D"texhtml"><var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">=CE=
=B3</var><sub>2</sub></span> denotes the population <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Excess_kurtosis" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Excess ku=
rtosis">excess kurtosis</a>. The excess kurtosis may be either known before=
hand for certain distributions, or estimated from the data.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standar=
d_deviation#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Confidence_interval_of_a_sa=
mpled_standard_deviation">Confidence interval of a sampled standard deviati=
on</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket=
">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DStandard_=
deviation&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: Confid=
ence interval of a sampled standard deviation"><span>edit</span></a><span c=
lass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Margin_of_error" title=
=3D"Margin of error">Margin of error</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Variance#Distribution_of_the_sample_variance" title=3D"Variance">Va=
riance =C2=A7&nbsp;Distribution of the sample variance</a>, and <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-distribution#Robust_parametric_=
modeling" title=3D"Student's t-distribution">Student's t-distribution =C2=
=A7&nbsp;Robust parametric modeling</a></div>
<p>The standard deviation we obtain by sampling a distribution is itself no=
t absolutely accurate, both for mathematical reasons (explained here by the=
 confidence interval) and for practical reasons of measurement (measurement=
 error). The mathematical effect can be described by the <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confidence_interval" title=3D"Confidence interval">c=
onfidence interval</a> or CI.=20
</p><p>To show how a larger sample will make the confidence interval narrow=
er, consider the following examples:=20
A small population of <span class=3D"texhtml"><var style=3D"padding-right: =
1px;">N</var> =3D 2</span> has only one degree of freedom for estimating th=
e standard deviation. The result is that a 95% CI of the SD runs from 0.45&=
nbsp;=C3=97&nbsp;SD to 31.9&nbsp;=C3=97&nbsp;SD; <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
