grees_of_freedom_(statistics)" title=3D"Degrees of freedom (statistics)">de=
grees of freedom</a> for error.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Bounds_on_standard_deviatio=
n">Bounds on standard deviation</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
w/index.php?title=3DStandard_deviation&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" =
title=3D"Edit section: Bounds on standard deviation"><span>edit</span></a><=
span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>For a set of <span class=3D"texhtml"><var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">=
N</var> &gt; 4</span> data spanning a range of values <span class=3D"texhtm=
l mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">R</span>, an upper bound on the standa=
rd deviation <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">s</s=
pan> is given by <span class=3D"texhtml"><var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;"=
>s</var> =3D 0.6<var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">R</var></span>.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Standard_deviation#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=20
An estimate of the standard deviation for <span class=3D"texhtml"><var styl=
e=3D"padding-right: 1px;">N</var> &gt; 100</span> data taken to be approxim=
ately normal follows from the heuristic that 95% of the area under the norm=
al curve lies roughly two standard deviations to either side of the mean, s=
o that, with 95% probability the total range of values <span class=3D"texht=
ml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">R</span> represents four standard dev=
iations so that <span class=3D"texhtml"><var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">=
s</var> =E2=89=88 <var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">R</var>/4</span>. This=
 so-called range rule is useful in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Sample_size" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sample size">sample size</a> e=
stimation, as the range of possible values is easier to estimate than the s=
tandard deviation. Other divisors <span class=3D"texhtml"><var style=3D"pad=
ding-right: 1px;">K</var>(<var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">N</var>)</span=
> of the range such that <span class=3D"texhtml"><var style=3D"padding-righ=
t: 1px;">s</var> =E2=89=88 <var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">R</var>/<var =
style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">K</var>(<var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">N<=
/var>)</span> are available for other values of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar=
" style=3D"font-style:italic;">N</span> and for non-normal distributions.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Standard_deviation#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Identities_and_mathematical=
_properties">Identities and mathematical properties</h2><span class=3D"mw-e=
ditsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DStandard_deviation&amp;action=3Dedi=
t&amp;section=3D14" title=3D"Edit section: Identities and mathematical prop=
erties"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span=
></span></div>
<p>The standard deviation is invariant under changes in <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Location_parameter" title=3D"Location parameter">loca=
tion</a>, and scales directly with the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Scale_parameter" title=3D"Scale parameter">scale</a> of the random var=
iable. Thus, for a constant <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-styl=
e:italic;">c</span> and random variables <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">X</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"=
font-style:italic;">Y</span>:
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
