t)^{2}}},\end{aligned}}}"></span>
</p><p>which means that the standard deviation is equal to the square root =
of the difference between the average of the squares of the values and the =
square of the average value.
</p><p>See computational formula for the variance for proof, and for an ana=
logous result for the sample standard deviation.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Interpretation_and_applicat=
ion">Interpretation and application</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/w/index.php?title=3DStandard_deviation&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D=
15" title=3D"Edit section: Interpretation and application"><span>edit</span=
></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Further information: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prediction_in=
terval" title=3D"Prediction interval">Prediction interval</a> and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confidence_interval" title=3D"Confidence =
interval">Confidence interval</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Comparison_standard_deviations.svg" class=3D"=
mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/com=
mons/thumb/f/f9/Comparison_standard_deviations.svg/500px-Comparison_standar=
d_deviations.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"400" height=3D"296" class=
=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"612" data-file-height=3D"453"></a><=
figcaption>Example of samples from two populations with the same mean but d=
ifferent standard deviations. Red population has mean 100 and SD 10; blue p=
opulation has mean 100 and SD 50.</figcaption></figure>
<p>A large standard deviation indicates that the data points can spread far=
 from the mean and a small standard deviation indicates that they are clust=
ered closely around the mean.
</p><p>For example, each of the three populations {0, 0, 14, 14}, {0, 6, 8,=
 14} and {6, 6, 8, 8} has a mean of 7. Their standard deviations are 7, 5, =
and 1, respectively. The third population has a much smaller standard devia=
tion than the other two because its values are all close to 7.  These stand=
ard deviations have the same units as the data points themselves. If, for i=
nstance, the data set {0, 6, 8, 14} represents the ages of a population of =
four siblings in years, the standard deviation is 5 years. As another examp=
le, the population {1000, 1006, 1008, 1014} may represent the distances tra=
veled by four athletes, measured in meters. It has a mean of 1007 meters, a=
nd a standard deviation of 5 meters.
</p><p>Standard deviation may serve as a measure of uncertainty.  In physic=
al science, for example, the reported standard deviation of a group of repe=
ated <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Measurement" title=3D"Measure=
ment">measurements</a> gives the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A=
ccuracy_and_precision" title=3D"Accuracy and precision">precision</a> of th=
ose measurements.  When deciding whether measurements agree with a theoreti=
cal prediction, the standard deviation of those measurements is of crucial =
importance: if the mean of the measurements is too far away from the predic=
tion (with the distance measured in standard deviations), then the theory b=
eing tested probably needs to be revised. This makes sense since they fall =
outside the range of values that could reasonably be expected to occur if t=
he prediction were correct and the standard deviation appropriately quantif=
ied.  See <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prediction_interval" tit=
le=3D"Prediction interval">prediction interval</a>.
</p><p>While the standard deviation does measure how far typical values ten=
d to be from the mean, other measures are available. An example is the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mean_absolute_deviation" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"Mean absolute deviation">mean absolute deviation</a>, whi=
ch might be considered a more direct measure of average distance, compared =
to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root-mean-square_deviation"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Root-mean-square deviation">root mean squar=
e distance</a> inherent in the standard deviation.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Application_examples">Appli=
cation examples</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DStandard_deviation&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D16" title=3D"Edit se=
ction: Application examples"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsec=
tion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The practical value of understanding the standard deviation of a set of =
values is in appreciating how much variation there is from the average (mea=
n).
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Experiment,_industrial_and_=
hypothesis_testing"><span id=3D"Experiment.2C_industrial_and_hypothesis_tes=
ting"></span>Experiment, industrial and hypothesis testing</h4><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DStandard_deviation&amp;act=
ion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D17" title=3D"Edit section: Experiment, industrial =
and hypothesis testing"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
"5 sigma" redirects here; not to be confused with <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Six_Sigma" title=3D"Six Sigma">Six Sigma</a>.</div>
<p>Standard deviation is often used to compare real-world data against a mo=
del to test the model.
For example, in industrial applications the weight of products coming off a=
 production line may need to comply with a legally required value. By weigh=
ing some fraction of the products an average weight can be found, which wil=
l always be slightly different from the long-term average. By using standar=
d deviations, a minimum and maximum value can be calculated that the averag=
ed weight will be within some very high percentage of the time (99.9% or mo=
re). If it falls outside the range then the production process may or not n=
eed to be corrected. Statistical tests such as these are particularly impor=
tant when the testing is relatively expensive. For example, if the product =
needs to be opened and drained and weighed, or if the product was otherwise=
 used up by the test.
</p><p>In experimental science, a theoretical model of reality is used. <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Particle_physics" title=3D"Particle p=
hysics">Particle physics</a> conventionally uses a standard of "<b>5 sigma<=
/b>" for the declaration of a discovery. A five-sigma level translates to o=
ne chance in 3.5 million that a random fluctuation would yield the result. =
This level of certainty was required in order to assert that a particle con=
sistent with the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Higgs_boson" titl=
e=3D"Higgs boson">Higgs boson</a> had been discovered in two independent ex=
periments at <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CERN" title=3D"CERN">=
CERN</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_deviation#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> also leadin=
g to the declaration of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/First_=
observation_of_gravitational_waves" title=3D"First observation of gravitati=
onal waves">first observation of gravitational waves</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard=
_deviation#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Weather">Weather</h4><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DStandard_deviation&amp=
;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D18" title=3D"Edit section: Weather"><span>edit=
</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>As a simple example, consider the average daily maximum temperatures for=
 two cities, one inland and one on the coast. It is helpful to understand t=
hat the range of daily maximum temperatures for cities near the coast is sm=
aller than for cities inland. Thus, while these two cities may each have th=
e same average maximum temperature, the standard deviation of the daily max=
imum temperature for the coastal city will be less than that of the inland =
city as, on any particular day, the actual maximum temperature is more like=
ly to be farther from the average maximum temperature for the inland city t=
han for the coastal one.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Finance">Finance</h4><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DStandard_deviation&amp=
;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D19" title=3D"Edit section: Finance"><span>edit=
</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In finance, standard deviation is often used as a measure of the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Risk#Finance" title=3D"Risk">risk</a> ass=
ociated with price-fluctuations of a given asset (stocks, bonds, property, =
etc.), or the risk of a portfolio of assets<sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_deviation#cit=
e_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup> (actively managed mutual funds, index mutual funds, =
or ETFs). Risk is an important factor in determining how to efficiently man=
age a portfolio of investments because it determines the variation in retur=
ns on the asset or portfolio and gives investors a mathematical basis for i=
nvestment decisions (known as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mode=
rn_portfolio_theory" title=3D"Modern portfolio theory">mean-variance optimi=
zation</a>). The fundamental concept of risk is that as it increases, the e=
xpected return on an investment should increase as well, an increase known =
as the risk premium. In other words, investors should expect a higher retur=
n on an investment when that investment carries a higher level of risk or u=
ncertainty. When evaluating investments, investors should estimate both the=
 expected return and the uncertainty of future returns. Standard deviation =
provides a quantified estimate of the uncertainty of future returns.
</p><p>For example, assume an investor had to choose between two stocks. St=
ock A over the past 20 years had an average return of 10 percent, with a st=
andard deviation of 20 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Percentage_=
point" title=3D"Percentage point">percentage points</a> (pp) and Stock B, o=
ver the same period, had average returns of 12 percent but a higher standar=
d deviation of 30 pp. On the basis of risk and return, an investor may deci=
de that Stock A is the safer choice, because Stock B's additional two perce=
ntage points of return is not worth the additional 10 pp standard deviation=
 (greater risk or uncertainty of the expected return). Stock B is likely to=
 fall short of the initial investment (but also to exceed the initial inves=
tment) more often than Stock A under the same circumstances, and is estimat=
ed to return only two percent more on average. In this example, Stock A is =
expected to earn about 10 percent, plus or minus 20 pp (a range of 30 perce=
nt to =E2=88=9210 percent), about two-thirds of the future year returns. Wh=
en considering more extreme possible returns or outcomes in future, an inve=
stor should expect results of as much as 10 percent plus or minus 60 pp, or=
 a range from 70 percent to =E2=88=9250 percent, which includes outcomes fo=
r three standard deviations from the average return (about 99.7 percent of =
probable returns).
</p><p>Calculating the average (or arithmetic mean) of the return of a secu=
rity over a given period will generate the expected return of the asset. Fo=
r each period, subtracting the expected return from the actual return resul=
ts in the difference from the mean.  Squaring the difference in each period=
 and taking the average gives the overall variance of the return of the ass=
et.  The larger the variance, the greater risk the security carries.  Findi=
ng the square root of this variance will give the standard deviation of the=
 investment tool in question.
</p><p>Financial time series are known to be non-stationary series, whereas=
 the statistical calculations above, such as standard deviation, apply only=
 to stationary series. To apply the above statistical tools to non-stationa=
ry series, the series first must be transformed to a stationary series, ena=
bling use of statistical tools that now have a valid basis from which to wo=
rk.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Geometric_interpretation">G=
eometric interpretation</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DStandard_deviation&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D20" title=3D=
"Edit section: Geometric interpretation"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>To gain some geometric insights and clarification, we will start with a =
population of three values, <span class=3D"texhtml"><var style=3D"padding-r=
ight: 1px;">x</var><sub>1</sub>, <var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">x</var>=
<sub>2</sub>, <var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">x</var><sub>3</sub></span>=
. This defines a point <span class=3D"texhtml"><var style=3D"padding-right:=
 1px;">P</var> =3D (<var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">x</var><sub>1</sub>,=
 <var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">x</var><sub>2</sub>, <var style=3D"padd=
ing-right: 1px;">x</var><sub>3</sub>)</span> in <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>=
R</b><sup>3</sup></span>. Consider the line <span class=3D"texhtml"><var st=
yle=3D"padding-right: 1px;">L</var> =3D {(<var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;=
">r</var>, <var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">r</var>, <var style=3D"paddin=
g-right: 1px;">r</var>)&nbsp;: <var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">r</var> =
=E2=88=88 <b>R</b>}</span>. This is the "main diagonal" going through the o=
rigin. If our three given values were all equal, then the standard deviatio=
n would be zero and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic=
;">P</span> would lie on <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:i=
talic;">L</span>. So it is not unreasonable to assume that the standard dev=
iation is related to the <i>distance</i> of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" st=
yle=3D"font-style:italic;">P</span> to <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">L</span>. That is indeed the case. To move orthogon=
ally from <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">L</span=
> to the point <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">P<=
/span>, one begins at the point:
</p><p><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=
